Linear equations in three variables can be visualized as planes in Cartesian space. To do this, we can think of each variable as a dimension, and the equation as a set of all points that satisfy the equation. For example, the equation

```
x + y + z = 3
```

represents the plane that passes through the origin (0, 0, 0) and has a slope of 1 in each direction.

We can visualize this plane by plotting the points that satisfy the equation. One way to do this is to start at the origin and then move 1 unit in the positive x-direction, 1 unit in the positive y-direction, and 1 unit in the positive z-direction. This will give us the point (1, 1, 1), which lies on the plane. We can continue in this way to plot more points on the plane.

Another way to visualize a linear equation in three variables is to use a 3D graphing calculator. This will allow us to see the plane in all its three dimensions.

Linear equations in three variables have many applications in physics, engineering, and computer science. For example, they can be used to model the motion of objects in space, the flow of fluids, and the behavior of electrical circuits.

Here are some specific examples of the applications of linear equations in three variables:

* In physics, linear equations can be used to model the motion of objects in space. For example, the equation

```
f(x, y, z) = -g * m * z
```

models the motion of a projectile in a gravitational field, where f(x, y, z) is the force acting on the projectile, g is the gravitational constant, m is the mass of the projectile, and z is the height of the projectile.
* In engineering, linear equations can be used to model the flow of fluids. For example, the equation

```
u(x, y) = -k * \nabla p
```

models the flow of a fluid in a two-dimensional channel, where u(x, y) is the velocity of the fluid, k is the viscosity of the fluid, and p is the pressure of the fluid.
* In computer science, linear equations can be used to solve problems such as linear programming and least squares problems. Linear programming is a technique for finding the best solution to a problem that is subject to a set of constraints. Least squares problems are used to fit a line or curve to a set of data points.

